(7) It is well known that Horace was a rather severe critic of the old poets, and especially of Plautus. Pareus says:—“There are, however, some who grate upon my ears, and who, relying on a sort of daring‚ strive by their jests to lessen and depreciate, not only in words but in reality, the praise of Plautus. And these are either old or more recent. Among the old despisers of Plautus, Horatius Flaccus is at the head of the band who, whether seriously or in jest, blubbered out against Plautus such a jeer as this.''
